# maintenence of codenames

when selecting names for methods, files, and anything else you have influence over it's name -- use these naming conventions.

1.  codename_structure
    A.  Use lowercase snake_case with a root (left most) term
        defining the broad concept.
    B.  Subject: the root term names the subject (domain,
        area, or entity) the codename refers to.
        1. Start a name using an existing root when possible
    C.  Subsequent terms refine object and action.
        1.  Object: what is acted on (e.g. state_list,
            card_rect).
        2.  Action: verb last (e.g. _get, _set, _build).

2.  term_rule
    A.  Keep terms short and singular.
    B.  Abbreviate frequently used terms.

3.  codename_maintenance
    A.  Engage iteratively to refine conventions.
    B.  Keep the index updated for easy sorting.
        1.  list all codenames in index.
        2.  Show count of occuance listed 36 characters in
        3.  Update paul/codename_index.txt every time
            codenames are added, removed, or changed.
    C.  Create/maintain codenames
        1.  Iterativly, in related groups, add commented
            lines with a double-underscore before the
            codename related to that code.

4.  name_index (doc/codename_index.md)
    A.  Keep lexicographic order by name.
    B.  Insert blank line when root term changes
        (first term before `_`).
    C.  Use `name : type` format.
    D.  Align `:` column vertically.
    E.  Keep `type` short and lowercase (`css`,
        `class`, `id`, `file`, `image`, `domain`,
        `section`, `field`).
